              <a href="tag-Chinese+Raisin+Tree+extract.html">Chinese Raisin Tree extract</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;
              <a href="tag-herbal+hangover+cure.html">herbal hangover cure</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;
              </div>
       
       
      
      <div id="news_contet_body" style="width:560px; overflow:hidden;" >
      

        
        <div align="center">&nbsp;<a target="_blank" href="http://www.whatsonxiamen.com/ent_images/d41aef6bd5d0d2b6b415b587_hangover_cure.jpg"><img alt="" width="500" height="333" src="http://www.whatsonxiamen.com/ent_images/d41aef6bd5d0d2b6b415b587_hangover_cure.jpg" /></a></div>
<div align="center"><font color="#0000ff">Hangover cure may be in the herb, says researcher </font></div>
<div align="center"><a href="http://www.whatsonxiamen.com/ent_images/d08c8ade8ef770105b50c300_herbal_hangover_cure.jpg"><font size="2"></font></a></div>
<div align="center"><a href="http://www.whatsonxiamen.com/ent_images/d08c8ade8ef770105b50c300_herbal_hangover_cure.jpg"><font size="2"><img alt="" width="460" height="296" src="http://www.whatsonxiamen.com/ent_images/d08c8ade8ef770105b50c300_herbal_hangover_cure.jpg" /></font></a></div>
<div align="center"><font color="#0000ff" size="2">Hovenia is an extract from the Chinese Raisin Tree.</font></div>
<div align="center"><font size="2">&nbsp;</font></div>
<div align="justify"><font size="2">If you&rsquo;re having trouble reading this because your head is pounding from too many drinks last night, help may be on the way. <br />
<br />
Of course, you&rsquo;ll have to wait until scientists perfect their theory. <br />
<br />
Researchers have uncovered a compound in an ancient Chinese herbal medicine that has been found to stop hangovers and to reduce alcohol dependency in rats, according to a recent study published in the Journal of Neuroscience. <br />
<br />
If the compound is proven to have the same effect in humans, it could help pave the way to a cure for alcoholism, said Dr. Jing Liang, the study&rsquo;s lead author and an associate professor of pharmacology at the University of California in Los Angeles, in an interview with Postmedia News. <br />
<br />
For others who enjoy an occasional drink but would rather not endure the pounding hangover headache the next day, taking the compound also could be &ldquo;an easy way to erase the uncomfortable feelings,&rdquo; said Liang. <br />
<br />
Hovenia is an extract from the Chinese Raisin Tree. <br />
<br />
In Asia, Liang said hovenia has been taken as an herbal supplement to treat hangovers for at least 500 years. <br />
<br />
However, the effectiveness of hovenia as a drug to treat alcohol dependency has never before been closely studied. <br />
<br />
Liang said she became interested in taking a closer look at hovenia when she noticed that when people consumed alcohol along with food cooked with hovenia &mdash; as it is also a spice used for cooking in Asia &mdash; they seemed to avoid getting drunk. <br />
<br />
In order to study how hovenia works, Liang said she needed to isolate the specific compound that was blocking the effect of alcohol. <br />
<br />
The answer turned out to be dihydromyricetin, or DHM. <br />
<br />
Liang and her research team at UCLA began testing the compound on rats. <br />
<br />
They devised a series of tests to determine what would happen to rats if they were given just alcohol, or alcohol along with DHM. <br />
<br />
For the group given alcohol, the rats&rsquo; behaviour when intoxicated was not unlike that of humans, she said. <br />
<br />
When you give a rat alcohol, they act &ldquo;totally like a human,&rdquo; said Liang. &ldquo;You give an animal alcohol and then they&rsquo;re drunk, and they lose consciousness. They go to sleep.&rdquo; <br />
<br />
But the rats who were given alcohol plus DHM, showed no signs of intoxication, Liang said. <br />
<br />
&quot;They don&rsquo;t (get) drunk,&rdquo; said Liang. &ldquo;It was amazing. I was so excited.&rdquo; <br />
<br />
The rats in the alcohol group slept for about 70 minutes, while those in the DHM group only slept for about 10 minutes. Others didn&rsquo;t sleep at all, she said. <br />
<br />
In another test, the researchers administered DHM to rats who were given alcohol for a prolonged period of time. Their symptoms of alcohol dependency were significantly reduced. <br />
<br />
&ldquo;From this experiment, even if you establish a high drinking level of alcohol and then give them DHM, their dependence will reduce,&rdquo; said Liang. <br />
<br />
The rats given DHM along with alcohol did not have any hangover symptoms either, she said. <br />
<br />
The next step, if she is able to secure enough funding, is to test the study&rsquo;s findings in human clinical trials, said Liang. <br />
<br />
She expects to see the same results in humans, and without any negative side effects. <br />
<br />
&quot;For more than 500 years (that hovenia has been used as a supplement), there have been no reports of poison or toxicity,&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s really safe.&rdquo; <br />
<br />
Liang&rsquo;s goal is to turn DHM into a medication, possibly in a gum, patch or spray-form, she said. She already has patented her idea. <br />
<br />
Alcohol-use disorders are a major public-health problem around the world, said Liang. <br />
<br />
In her study, she wrote that there are only three medications &mdash; oral naltrexone, acamprosate and disulfiram &mdash; currently approved for treating alcohol dependence by the U.S. Food and Drug Administration. <br />
<br />
However, Liang said these drugs have major side-effects and have not been proven effective in treating the disorders. <br />
<br />
Bernard Le Foll, a pharmacology professor at the University of Toronto, said the study&rsquo;s findings are &ldquo;very promising&rdquo; for the treatment of alcohol addiction. <br />
<br />
&quot;I think it&rsquo;s very interesting,&rdquo; he told Postmedia News. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s building on the use of an old plant in Chinese medicine and they seem to have been able to isolate what seems to be the active ingredient.&rdquo; <br />
<br />
However, Le Foll does not recommend people start taking hovenia to treat their hangovers just yet. <br />
<br />
&quot;More experiments need to be done. We need to validate this in human subjects,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;But what is clear from this experiment is that . . . some drugs appear to accelerate the elimination of alcohol from the body, and also it seems to reduce the desire to drink alcohol.&rdquo; <br />
<br />
<strong>SOURCE: <a  target="_blank"  rel="nofollow" href="http://www.vancouversun.com/health/Hangover+cure+herb+says+UCLA+researcher/5997380/story.html"  >Vancouver Sun</a></strong></font></div>
<div align="justify"><font size="2">&nbsp;</font></div>
